Below is a zero-latency design for the optimizer hot-path and a fast on-demand polygon extractor for Panel/Bokeh.

Key design choice to keep your 10 ms / 10k iterations intact:

compute_all() computes only the scalar dead-space areas A and B using an O(n + R) run-length envelope method (no polygon tracing, no BFS, no allocations).

Polygon coordinates for Area A and Area B are computed on-demand for a chosen iteration (slider), using a small uniform grid at a configurable step size dead_cell_size_ (this is your finite-step control variable).

This satisfies:

Dead-space scalars available in compute_all() and Metrics

Dead-space polygons accessible via pybind (like bbox)

No heavy branching/selection inside compute_all()

Scalable to 1000 blocks (hot-path is linear; polygon path scales with grid cells, not blocks)

Algorithm (fast + scalable)
Definitions

BBox: axis-aligned bounding box of all blocks.

Outer envelope (row-span hull) at resolution dead_cell_size_:

For each grid row (y-slab), compute:

min_col[row] = min block-left column among blocks intersecting this row

max_col[row] = max block-right column among blocks intersecting this row

Envelope row segment is [min_col[row], max_col[row]] (if any block intersects the row).

This envelope is extremely fast to compute because it is just range updates while scanning blocks.

Dead-space areas

Let:

bbox_row_width_cells = bx1 - bx0 + 1

env_row_width_cells = max_col[row] - min_col[row] + 1 for rows with blocks

cell_area = dead_cell_size_^2

Then:

Area A (“between bbox and envelope”)
For each row within bbox rows:

If envelope exists: A_cells += bbox_row_width_cells - env_row_width_cells

Else: A_cells += bbox_row_width_cells
AreaA = A_cells * cell_area

Envelope area: Env_cells += env_row_width_cells → EnvArea = Env_cells * cell_area

Area B (“inside envelope but not occupied by blocks”)
When overlaps are negligible: union area ≈ sum(block areas) = total_rect_area_
AreaB = max(0, EnvArea - total_rect_area_)

Overlap gating (no trade-off with overlap)

Dead-space constraint is applied only when:

overlap_metric <= deadspace_overlap_threshold_

Else:

AreaA = 0, AreaB = 0

polygon outputs are empty

dead-space penalty is 0

This removes overlap↔deadspace tradeoff entirely: overlap must be solved first.

Polygons (on-demand)

When slider requests polygons for iteration k:

Build envelope mask from row segments (grid).

Build block occupancy mask by rasterizing block rectangles into grid cells.

Build:

A_mask = bbox_mask & ~envelope_mask

B_mask = envelope_mask & ~block_mask (only if overlap below threshold)

Convert each mask into boundary polygons using boundary-edge stitching (very fast on small grids).

Finite-step control: dead_cell_size_ controls polygon fidelity vs speed.

